cover is addressed to Miss Helen Hiseman in Honolulu; "Hawaii" or "T.H."
was omitted since Rodgers was place it in the mail in Honolulu as he did
the other two. This lost cover also carries a manuscript notes "Via /
Transpific (sic) flight Favor of / Commander John Rodgers / August 31 - 25"
And of equal interest, this cover stlll contains an enclosure, in the same
handwriting as the address and manuscript cover note, that reads:
Hello Helen and you all. Isn't this fine to get a letter
by air from San Francisco to Honolulu.
Commander Rodgers
is kind enought to take it. Love to all. Aunt Kate
Helen Hiseman was a young girl at that time and had an interest in stampa.
This was not the only letter sent by
â€¢ via
John Rodgers, to Hawaii. The recipient of the 1llustrated lost cover
reports that another went to her cousin and that three others were sent
to people then prominent in Honolulu - a former governor, the manager of
Waikiki's then leading hotel, and a social leader of the Islands. The
whereabouts of these other lost covers is not known; undoubtedly some if
not all have been truly lost. But Commander John Rodgers probably carried
at least seven covers on his 1925 flight from California to Hawaii.
These lost covers do differ in one way from the two recognized
in the AAMC; these lost five were delivered through the U.S.Mail in
Honolulu rather than being hand-delivered by Rodgers.
Information or comments about the lost John Rodgers covers would
be appreciated.
